John Edward: Knowledge of languages is crucial for global citizens
Scottish stand-alone schools enjoy a reputation for academic excellence, and this continued in 2018 with another set of outstanding exam results, reinforced by individual and collective successes in sport, the arts, music and other community endeavors.
With more than 30,000 students across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council for Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the highest level of service to their students and their parents.
Independent schools want to prepare their students for further and higher education, their chosen career path and the place they have as global citizens.
As an education sector that can design and implement a customized school curriculum, we see that modern languages are still a popular and desirable elective in schools.
Nelson Mandela once said, “If you talk to a person in a language he understands, the conversation sticks to his memory.
But if you speak to a person in his native language, the words are imprinted on his heart.”
This is a good reminder that we should not rely solely on English when we want to establish relations and trust with people from other countries.
This year’s results of recent exams show that languages are at the top of the scale with the highest success rates in independent schools.
68% of students who studied a foreign language achieved an excellent grade.
Data collected from 74 schools in the Scottish Council for Independent Schools (SCIS) showed that 72 per cent of pupils achieved an excellent grade in Mandarin, while 72 per cent of German pupils, 69 per cent of French pupils and 63 per cent of Spanish pupils also achieved an excellent grade.
This proves that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as a key knowledge that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages are treated as elective subjects in the curricula of independent schools and elsewhere in the same way as subjects in the fields of natural sciences, technology, engineering and mathematics.
A 2014 survey by the UK’s Employment and Training Commission found that 17 per cent of the reasons employers struggle to fill vacancies are due to a lack of language skills.
Therefore, knowledge of languages is becoming increasingly necessary in preparing young people for their future career path.
With future job opportunities requiring language skills, these skills are essential in a global world.
If a person learns a second language, regardless of the career path he chooses, with such lifelong knowledge, he has a great advantage in the future.
A multilingual person who can communicate directly with people from foreign countries automatically takes precedence over the competition.
A 2013 YouGov survey of more than 4,000 adults in the UK found that 75 percent of people did not speak a foreign language well enough to speak, with French being the only language spoken by a two-digit percentage of respondents, or 15 percent.
Therefore, investing in language learning is important for today’s children.
With knowledge of several languages, especially those from developing countries, children are more likely to find suitable employment.
In Scotland, schools differ in the languages they teach.
Many schools focus on more classical modern languages, while others teach the languages that are expected to be most relevant to the UK in 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Regardless of the interests of your child, in independent schools it will always be possible to choose a number of languages taught by specialists in this field.
Scottish independent schools are committed to providing a learning environment that prepares and equips children with the skills they need to succeed, no matter what the future holds.
In the global business environment, it cannot be denied that languages remain extremely important for the future of the country, so this must also be expressed in education.
In fact, modern languages should be treated as “international communication skills.”
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to young people in Scotland.
I'll be honest with you.
John Edward is Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools.
