North Korea: 'We will not unilaterally disarm without confidence'
North Korea’s foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that the continued implementation of sanctions is creating growing mistrust in the United States and that under such conditions, North Korea will certainly not unilaterally give up its nuclear weapons.
Ri Yong Ho told the annual General Assembly of the world body that North Korea had taken a number of “important measures in good faith” over the past year, such as halting nuclear and missile tests, tearing down a nuclear test site and promising not to spread nuclear weapons and technology.
“However, we do not see an appropriate response from the United States,” he said.
“Without trust in the United States, we will not be sure of national security, and under such conditions, we will not be the first to unilaterally disarm.”
While Ri echoed North Korea’s well-known complaints about Washington’s resistance to a gradual approach to nuclear disarmament, in which North Korea would be rewarded for taking gradual action, his statement was important because it did not immediately reject unilateral nuclear disarmament, as Pyongyang has done in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump from the first summit between the current US president and the North Korean leader, held in Singapore on June 12. At that time, Kim pledged to work for the “nuclear disarmament of the Korean Peninsula”, while Trump promised North Korea security assurances.
North Korea wants an official end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States has said Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
The United States has also called for the lifting of international sanctions on North Korea.
“The U.S. insists that we must first disarm ourselves with nuclear weapons, and increases the pressure with sanctions to forcefully achieve its goals, and even opposes the declaration of an end to the war,” Ri said.
“The idea that sanctions could bring us to our knees is an unrealistic hope for people who don’t even know us.
The problem is that the continued implementation of sanctions further deepens our mistrust.”
Ri made no mention of plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump, which the U.S. president outlined at the U.N. assembly earlier this week.
Instead, the minister highlighted the three meetings between Kim and South Korean President Moon Jae-in over the past five months, adding: “If we had discussed the problem of nuclear disarmament with South Korea rather than the United States, the nuclear disarmament of the Korean Peninsula would not have reached such a deadlock.”
Still, the tone of Rio’s speech was completely different from last year when he told the United Nations General Assembly that an attack on the continental United States with North Korean missiles was inevitable after “Mr. Wicked President” Trump called Kim a “missile man” on a suicide mission.
This year, Trump, who threatened to “totally destroy” North Korea last year, praised Kim and his courage in taking disarmament measures at the United Nations assembly, but said there was still much work to be done and that sanctions must remain in place until North Korea disarms.
On Wednesday, Trump said there was no timetable, adding: “It could be two years, three years or five months — it doesn’t matter.”
China and Russia are of the opinion that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the measures taken.
U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the U.N. Security Council on Thursday: “The imposition of sanctions by the Security Council must resolutely continue without exception until we recognize the complete, final and verified state of nuclear disarmament.”
The Security Council has unanimously adopted additional sanctions against North Korea since 2006 to deny funding for North Korea's nuclear weapons and ballistic missile programs.
Pompeo met with Rio on the margins of the United Nations General Assembly and later said he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for a second summit.
Pompeo has visited North Korea three times this year, but his last visit did not end well.
When he left Pyongyang in July, he said there had been progress, and North Korea criticized him hours later, saying his demands were "gangsterish".
At a meeting with Moon this month, North Korea pledged to demolish a missile test station and nuclear test infrastructure if the United States took “appropriate measures.”
Kim said Moon was referring to the “appropriate measures” that Trump promised in Singapore and measures to normalize relations with Washington.
Harvard University students attend a course where they learn how to take enough time to rest
The goal of this year’s new course at Harvard University is to teach all undergraduate students how to get more sleep. With such a course, they want to fight the growing machismo culture of “full-time” learning, in which strength accumulates with caffeine.
A university professor has found that students at the world’s best university often don’t know the basics about taking care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham Women’s Hospital, designed the course, which is the first of its kind in the United States.
He decided to conduct such a course after his lecture on the impact of lack of sleep on learning.
At the end of the lecture, a girl approached him and said, “Why do I only know this now that I’m in my senior year?”
She said that no one had ever told her how important sleep was, and the professor told The Daily Telegraph that this surprised him.
The course, which is held for the first time this year, talks about the key importance of good sleep habits for academic and sports success as well as for improving overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university’s health services, says they opted for such a course when they found that students were significantly sleep-deprived during the week.
The one-hour course includes a number of interactive tasks.
In one section, there is an image of a dorm door where students can click on coffee cups, curtains, sports shoes, and books to gain information on the impact of caffeine and light, the impact of sleep deprivation on athletic success, and the importance of a sleep routine.
In the second section, participants learn that long-term lack of sleep can increase the risk of heart failure, stroke, depression, and cancer.
A map of the student settlement with interactive icons encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
“We know that the behavior of students will not change immediately.
But we believe they have the right to know these facts, just as they have the right to know how their health is affected by cigarette smoking,” adds Professor Czeisler.
The professor says that the culture of pride is still present in the “all-night learning experience”, adding that modern technology and increasing pressure on students, resulting in a lack of sleep, represent growing problems.
Professor Czeisler says that a sufficient amount of quality sleep should be the “secret weapon” of students to combat stress, exhaustion and anxiety. Thus, they can also avoid gaining weight – the brain goes into starvation mode due to lack of sleep, which makes students constantly hungry.
A 19-year-old Californian student of chemical and physical biology, Raymond So, helped Professor Czeisler design the course. Last year, during his freshman year at Harvard, he attended one of the professor’s lectures.
He says the lecture opened his eyes and encouraged him to conduct a course throughout the campus.
He hopes that in the next phase, postgraduate students will be able to ask to complete a similar study program before enrolling in a competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler recommends students to set an alarm clock for sleeping as well as waking up. He also wants to draw their attention to the harmful effects of “blue light” emitted by electronic screens and LED lighting, as they can cause an imbalance of the circadian rhythm, making it difficult to fall asleep.
