Almanac: Inventor of the Geiger counter
We present a page from the almanac of our Sunday issues: on September 30, 1882, that is, on this day more than 136 years ago, Johannes Wilhelm “Hans” Geiger was born in Germany, who later became a world-famous physicist.
Geiger developed a method of detecting and measuring radioactivity, which was the basis for the development of a device called the Geiger counter.
It has become a staple in the scientific world, and it has also gained its place in pop culture, for example in the 1950 film “Bells of Coronado”, in which Roy Rogers and Dale Evans play cowboy scientists:
Man: “What the hell is this?”
Rogers: "This is a Geiger counter. It's used to look for radioactive minerals like uranium.
When you put on your headphones, you can hear the effect of the radioactivity in the materials on the atoms.”
Evans: “Oh my gosh, they’re really talking now!”
“Hans” Geiger died in 1945, just days before his 63rd birthday.
The invention with his name lives on.
