HIV/AIDS: China reports 14% increase in new cases
China has announced a 14 percent increase in the number of citizens living with HIV and AIDS.
Health officials say more than 820,000 people in the country are affected.
In the second quarter of 2018 alone, about 40,000 new cases were reported.
In the vast majority of new cases, the disease is transmitted through sexual intercourse, which represents a change compared to the past.
HIV has spread rapidly in parts of China due to blood transfusions.
However, according to Chinese health officials at a conference in Yunnan province, the number of people infected with HIV in this way has fallen to almost zero.
However, the number of people living with HIV and AIDS in China is still increasing by 100,000 per year.
Sexual transmission of HIV is a serious problem in the Chinese LGBT community.
Homosexuality was decriminalized in China in 1997, but discrimination against LGBT people remains widespread.
Because conservative values still apply in the country, according to research, 70-90% of men who have sex with men eventually marry a woman.
The disease is often transmitted due to inadequate protection in sexual relations in such relationships.
Since 2003, the Chinese government has promised universal access to HIV medicines as part of efforts to address the problem.
