What is the Global Citizen Festival and has it contributed in any way to poverty reduction?
This Saturday, New York will host the Global Citizens Festival, an annual music event featuring a truly extraordinary array of stars and with the same extraordinary mission: to end poverty in the world.
Tens of thousands of people will take part in the festival, this time for the seventh time. They will occupy the Grand Canyon of Central Park not only to enjoy the performances of musicians such as Janet Jackson, Cardi B and Shawn Mendes, but also to arouse interest in the real purpose of the event, i.e. the elimination of extreme poverty by 2030.
The Global Citizens Festival, launched in 2012, is an extension of the Global Citizens Project, an international advocacy group that hopes to eradicate poverty by increasing the number of people actively fighting it.
To receive a free ticket to the event (unless you were willing to pay for a VIP ticket), concertgoers had to complete a series of tasks or “acts” such as volunteering, a letter to a world leader, a phone call, or any other meaningful way to raise awareness of their poverty eradication goal.
How successful is the Global Citizen movement, which has 12 years left to achieve its goal?
Is the idea of rewarding people with a free concert the right way to convince them to demand action, or is it just another example of so-called “clictivism” – creating the belief that people actually have a significant impact on the situation by signing an online petition or tweeting?
According to the Global Citizen movement, more than 19 million “actions” of its supporters have been recorded since 2011 in pursuit of a series of different goals.
He says these actions have helped world leaders make commitments and policies worth more than $37 billion, which are expected to affect the lives of more than 2.25 billion people by 2030.
In early 2018, the group stated that its actions were the result of 390 commitments and messages, on the basis of which at least USD 10 billion had already been paid or collected.
The group estimates that the funds raised so far have directly affected nearly 649 million people worldwide.
Some of the key pledges are The Power of Nutrition, a partnership of investors and decision makers committed to “helping children realize their full potential,” who have pledged $35 million in aid to Rwanda to help end malnutrition after receiving more than 4,700 tweets from the Global Citizens movement.
“With the support of the UK government, donors, national governments and global citizens like you, we can put the social injustice of malnutrition in historical archives,” said Tracey Ullman, Ambassador of the Power of Food Partnership, at a concert in London in April 2018.
The group also said that the government, after more than 5,000 actions called on the UK to improve the nutrition of mothers and children, had announced it would co-finance the Power of Nutrition project, which will reach 5 million women and children through nutrition measures.
In response to one of the most common questions on the site, “Why do you think we can end extreme poverty?”,
The Global Citizen movement responded: “It will be a long and hard road – sometimes we will fall and fail.
But like the great civil rights movement and the fight against apartheid before us, we will succeed, because together we are stronger.
Among some of the performers who will perform at this year’s event in New York are Janet Jackson, the Weeknd, Shawn Mendes, Cardi B and Janelle Monáe. The event will be hosted by Deborra-Lee Furness and Hugh Jackman.
