The inventor of the World Wide Web plans to launch a new Internet to combat Google and Facebook
Tim Berners-Lee, the inventor of the World Wide Web, is starting a startup company that will compete with Facebook, Amazon and Google.
The latest project of this technology legend, Inrupt, is a company that builds on Berners-Lee’s open-source Solid platform.
Solid allows users to choose where their data is stored and who has access to which information.
In an exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee joked that Inrupt's intention was to "rule the world".
“We decided to do it now,” he said of the new company.
“This is a historic moment.”
The application uses Solid platform technology, which allows users to create a "personal data storage" or POD
This may include contact information, task lists, a calendar, a music library, and other personal and professional tools.
It’s similar to having Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack, and Spotify all available in one browser and at the same time.
The peculiarity of personal data storage is that the user can fully determine who can access which information.
The company calls this “personal data empowerment.”
Chief Executive Officer John Bruce says the company’s idea is to bring together the resources, processes, and relevant skills that will make access to the Solid platform possible for everyone.
The company currently consists of Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform acquired by IBM, a handful of developers hired to work on the project, and a community of volunteer programmers.
Already this week, technology developers around the world could create their own decentralized applications using the tools available on Inrupt’s website.
Berners-Lee said that he and the group "are not discussing with Facebook and Google whether we could introduce a complete change that could end all of their business models overnight."
“We’re not asking for permission.”
In a post on Medium on Saturday, Berners-Lee wrote that Inrupt’s goal is to “provide commercial energy and an ecosystem to protect the integrity and quality of the new web built on the Solid platform.”
