Red tide news: Concentrations along the coasts of Pinellas, Manatee and Saratosa districts are decreasing
The latest report from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Conservation Commission (FWC) shows an overall decrease in red tide concentrations in parts of the Tampa Bay area.
In the counties of Pinellas, Manatee, Saratosa, Charlotte and Collier, the FWC reported more diffuse flowering, indicating a decrease in concentrations.
The red tide extends approximately 130 miles from the coast north of Pinellas County to the southern Lee County.
The patches look about 10 miles off the coast of Hillsborough County, but in fewer places than last week.
Red tide has also been observed in Pasco County.
During the past week, average concentrations have been reported in and around Pinellas County, low to high concentrations along the coast of Hillsborough County, basic to high concentrations in Manatee County, basic to high concentrations in and around Saratosa County, and high to high concentrations in Saratosa County and along its coast, basic to medium concentrations in and around the District of Charlotte.
Respiratory irritation continues to be reported from the counties of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier.
There have been no reports of respiratory distress from Northwest Florida in the past week.
